 ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Herendeen  .","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArrachtáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Arrachtán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>arrachtach</i> ‘mighty, powerful’.","Irish: in Kerry, this name was adopted as an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hIongardail</b>, later <b>Ó hUrdáil</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Iongardal</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Herington","meanings":["English: variant of   Harrington   or   Herrington  ."]},{"name":"Herrington","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Heronden in Tenterden (Kent) or Herrington in Houghton (Durham). The Kent placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Hȳra</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>denn</i> ‘pasture’, while the Durham placename may come from Old English <i>hæring</i> ‘rocky place’ (from <i>hær</i> ‘rock, heap of stones’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>) or <i>hæren</i> ‘rocky’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","variant of   Harrington  ."]},{"name":"Herendeen","meanings":["Altered form of English   Harrington  ."]},{"name":"Arrington","meanings":["English:","variant of   Harrington   with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","possibly a habitational name from Arrington, a place in Cambridgeshire, named from an Old English byname, <i>Earn(a)</i>, meaning ‘eagle’ + <i>-inga-</i> ‘people or followers of’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John de Harrington 1st Baron of Aldingham was born about 1280, in Aldingham, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Haverington, was 51 and his mother, Agnes Cansfield, was 31. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Joan Dacre. He died on 2 July 1347, in his hometown, at the age of 68, and was buried in Cartmel, Cumbria, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1280–2 July 1347"